```C#
[Fact]
public void SetNanoSeconds()
{
   string firstFile = GetTestFilePath();
    File.WriteAllText(firstFile, "");
            
    var t = DateTime.UtcNow;
    File.SetLastWriteTimeUtc(firstFile, t);
    long firstFileTicks = File.GetLastWriteTimeUtc(firstFile).Ticks;
    long secondFileTicks = t.Ticks;

     Console.WriteLine(firstFileTicks);
     Console.WriteLine(secondFileTicks);
      //Assert.True(t == File.GetLastWriteTimeUtc(firstFile));
      Assert.True(firstFileTicks == secondFileTicks, $"First File Ticks\t{firstFileTicks}\nSecond File Ticks\t{secondFileTicks}");
}
```
Both the asserts fail here
```
  636717138509940000
  636717138509946880
System.IO.Tests.File_GetSetTimes.SetNanoSeconds [FAIL]
 First File Ticks	636717138509940000
 Second File Ticks	636717138509946880
```

This is due to the fact that while setter we use ```DataTimeOffset.ToUnixTimeMilliseconds()``` function to get the ticks, which drops the last few bits. 

We can define a new public api called ```DateTimeOffset.ToUnixTimeNanoseconds()``` in DateTimeOffset class. We have some of the constants setup here https://github.com/dotnet/coreclr/blob/master/src/System.Private.CoreLib/shared/System/DateTimeOffset.cs#L40 to get the correct values

